Back here after six months. I broke out crying during the last scene where Tiffany is crying and lamenting about her appearance and general depression. Feeling unloved, undeserving, inadequate and disgusting. As if you're trying to mock something you will never be. I used to project against transgender issues and it's community for such a long time. When I realized I was Queer in general the self-hate intensified until I landed in the hospital for the fifth time after trying to take my life. Something about it was different and I decided to try to explore what was causing me so much pain.      I have always been 'masculine,' I don't know what exactly that means. Ever since I was a child Id simply want to play with the boys, dress like them and be with them. Everything about their lives and wanting to belong intrigued me. Up until I was twelve I didn't realize that I didn't want to just be friends with them. When I first began puberty I experienced an immediate disconnect to my body. I didn't love it, I didn't want it. When it came to fapping I would imagine I had a penis and could only get off then or imagine I was touching another woman which sent me into a gay panic as I was extremely and hopelessly attracted to women. I tried to focus on every slight male attraction I had to make myself 'straight-ish,' at the very least. I tried/try to convince myself that I'm just a tomboy. But once you wake up wanting to cut off your breasts and magically grow a penis and cry about it in your sleep or even just try to turn yourself 'off' when you're having sex because It just feels otherworldy... I just didn't understand why this was happening. This happened before I even had any real interaction or information with/about being trans.     After so many painful years of being in the closet in general... I wanted to go ahead and dabble with the idea of being a trans man. However, that really didn't work out for me because I only seemed to get worse mentally.    As of now, I'm about to be 20 and well, I'd say I'm genderqueer but the truth is I'm really just terrified to say what I feel like I am... I have never allowed myself to date women and whenever I try to tell my boyfriend about what I feel like he expresses that he wouldn't want to be in the relationship anymore which is rational, he's a straight man after all... I don't want to lose him. I'm in a very scary spot in my life and this is terrifying to even write. My family would disown me, I don't think I'd be able to fathom transitioning, I would lose so much. I'm too scared to try.     But Natalie, thank you for opening the bag I didn't wanna touch for so long. Thank you.

When Jackie Jackson went off on Tiffany  Contrapoints is when Natalie makes her central point: because Tiffany Tumbles's presentation of transgenderism fails to challenge the status quo or at least ask the status quo to genuinely accept the dignity of transgender persons, Tiffany Tumbles can never be truly accepted by those who benefit from the status quo.  Merely commenting upon her personal decision to undergo plastic surgery to appear more like a woman immediately threatens the status quo and jolts awake lingering and unresolved transphobia.  Unlike a 'genuine woman' who may choose to undergo plastic surgery, an 'individual who has chosen to identify woman'''s decision to undergo the same procedure is suddenly a bizarre outsider succumbing to 'backwards social norms' and 'not truly understanding what it means to be woman.'  Tiffany's outsider-status is maintained if she doesn't demand that the world doesn't truly and honestly accept her as a woman.  And she fails to realize that unless the demand is made, they never will.

I'm an NB SJW who has cis privilege, and really, people who don't experience dysphoria or the oppression one experiences when transitioning need to stop claiming legitimacy to speak for all trans issues.   For a long time I was the only leader of the disability and mental illness subgroup of a major trans activist organization in  my city.  The rules were supposed to be that every subgroup have 2 leaders who were both trans, and at least one should be POC.  My co-leader, who was a black trans man, stepped down a few weeks after the formation of the group, because of school and his personal life.  No one else felt qualified to be one of the leaders, before or after this happened and that privilege is a big reason why. Most of our members were brand new to activism and hadn't attended a protest before. I have never had to worry that if I'm arrested protesting, I'd end up a lone woman in a male jail cell.  Most of them couldn't commit to attendance at every meeting because if they didn't have a ride they had to take public transit, sometimes after dark, and couldn't be sure they could do this without getting murdered. This is somewhat not an irrational fear for anyone AFAB, but it isn't so consuming that I can't take transit, and besides, I didn't need to, because I had a car that I payed for with my job where I went by my preferred gender-neutral name with no issue because I told them it was just my nickname.  Throughout the whole process I continued to tell the other leaders of other subgroups that I self identify as non-binary but not trans, that I was a trans ally filling this position only until someone more qualified could make the time commitment, and was met with constant denial and told that I don't need dysphoria to be allowed in trans-only spaces, was offered trans-only subsidized housing that I turned down, having to explain that we all have a housing crisis but I'm not actually facing housing discrimination. The worst trans-related oppression I ever have to experience is being annoyed that strangers keep calling me ma'am. But since I'm leader of the disability group (and do actually have mental illnesses) I continued to be the one all the other leaders referred people to when their dysphoria got so bad they felt suicidal and the NT's got all freaked out and scared they couldn't handle it.  I was the one who was supposed to know where you can go to get help for legitimate mental illness without it being used to deny your right to transition.  I don't know. And whether or not I get to include myself in the trans umbrella isn't the biggest concern I have for the trans community right now.    In no way does this make it okay for white trans women to suddenly decide racism is the solution to everything, but being called an awful truscum transmedicalist for demanding these issues take up more of the focus than the constant reiterations of 'you're valid and your identity is valid and always make sure you ask and don't assume pronouns' and celebrating deviating from gender norms that seems to take up all of trans social media, well. That's a real thing.  And it's leaving many trans people without a community to turn to.  If they were gonna become trump supporters as soon as they felt alienated anyway, no great loss, but those aren't the only trans people we're abandoning either.  If you're not cis and you don't struggle with access to hormones, life-threatening dysphoria, being murdered by your lover, or the fear of being incarcerated in a facility for the wrong gender, you should really prioritize fighting for the people who do face those things

I'm from Bulgaria. The LGBT community here has the same representation problem this video highlights. We have no real media representation outside hetero-accepted stereotypes, so the only way we get it is by being out in our real lives and influencing the people around us to actually consider the LGBT community. Generaly speaking, most bulgarians have the 'keep it at home' mentality about everything non-cishet. Enter Sofia Pride or what passes for a pride parade in Bulgaria. It usually has about 2000 young, white, gays and lesbians (don't think I've ever seen a trans person). Every time it comes around the media explodes with comments 'I don't mind gay people, but why do they have to have a parade/shuv it down my throat' and 'How will I explain this to little Goshko!'. A lot of LGBTQ+ people don't attend the parade and want it to stop it from happening, because they believe it's overexposure and that it ruining our image and halting progress.  It's toxic internalised homophobia, of course, but it's hard not to empathise with them a little bit. I mean, when Pride's not happening people sort of forget about the LGBT community and we sort of do what we want, but when it rolls around, people get their pitchforks. It's easy to look at Pride and say 'What are you even proud of? Just shut up and let things happen on their own, you attention seeking gnats! We were doing just fine!'. Basicly, they want acceptance, but don't want to fight for understanding. They don't want to get their hands(and image) dirty, because it's easier to be a cishet lapdog.

As Me being a cis man, the part where she exclaims that she 'mutilated herself' was simply heartbreaking. It's sobering to realize that many trans women probably genuinely feel this way towards themselves, since dysphoria about one's own gender is difficult to get over, since even when you do 'fix' all the things that made you feel horrible, you might find soemthing else that you're not satisfied with, a la 'I fixed my nose but now my brow stands out'.  It also kind of goes that way for cis people, to some _much lower and less extreme extent,_ when we dislike our appearances. For example, I generally don't like my facial structure (because I'm pretty effeminate in body shape aside from the biggest bone structure differences like my shoulder/waist ratio) so I decided to grow my hair out. But now my hair goes down well past the middle of my back, and I find something else to hate, like my almost complete lack of facial hair.  Basically, what I'm trying to say in a really awkward way is, this video spoke to me in a way I wouldn't expect a video about internalised transphobia to do, which is eye-opening for a cis person who really wants to be an ally.

You take a position against traps as transphobic in this video, and say that it's been used as a slur against you. I have always considered traps and trans women to be two separate concepts, defined as opposites by the unobjectionable fact that traps identify as male but trans women identify as female.  Traps, like futanari (girls with big dicks), represent one or both of two sexual concepts. The first is a safely expressed attraction to male sexual characteristics - even though you like looking at the penis and thinking about sexual activity with someone with a penis, the person is still presenting as female and thus your sexual identity is protected. This is the essence of the 'trickery.' It's not that those darn trans woman are making me like dick, it's the taboo nature of liking dick but being 'forced' into it by someone who takes advantage of your 'real' attraction to women. You can consider traps as thus a step on the way to ending transphobia and homophobia because they allow straight men to express their sexuality and thus not feel as threatened or confused by queer people. Trapping is really about protecting your sexuality, not so much about genderbending.  The second fetish concept is that the penis is a large part of male sexual development. It's the source of good feelings and sexual bliss, and cumming is an obvious sign of arousal and enjoyment. Translating the penis onto a women allows men to combine those contradictory aspects of their sexuality. You can look at male trap fetishes as similar in concept to the idea of making women 'squirt,' because men grow up associating orgasms with ejaculation, which becomes confusing or dissatisfying when they learn that women don't orgasm as visibly or distinctly. A futa or trap, on the other hand, has a predictable, and thus comforting, sexual expression. Again, this is a part of men expressing sexuality and not feeling threatened or confused. This one is actually debatably more healthy for queer representation than the previous because the futa or trap in this one identifies as female. The only issue is that it leads to expectations of sex with a trans girl as being different from sex with a woman, when in actuality sex with a trans woman is pretty much just anal with a woman. HRT makes pee pee no worky so good, and gender dysphoria means that a trans woman is not going to WANT to ejaculate or have you treat her genitals like a penis instead of a big ol clitoris.  You can talk back and forth about the dubious morality or positivity behind turning transgender women and cross-dressers into sexual objects for male pleasure, and whether THAT is transphobic or not. As a man, I don't think it's avoidable. You can fight against hatred, and you can fight against confusion or misinformation, but fighting love? I'm not sure that one is possible.  Remember that this is just in reference to the very specific fetish of someone who presents as female but has a working penis (futanari in the case of identifying as a woman, trap in the case of identifying as a man, trans girl in real life). Otokonoko means boy in Japanese. In anime and in otaku culture otokonoko describes pretty much the same thing as the word trap does in the English language. It's not really the same as trans or a cross dressing man (otoko no musume in Japanese), it describes a non transe young man or boy who looks exactly like a woman when crossdressing but is 100% biological male, hence the name 'trap'. No one would call a post op trans woman a trap (though it's arguable whether she should disclose her biological gender before dating someone. To me it's not really important, but for some people it is, and I can fully understand why they'd think such information is important and I don't believe this has anything to do with transphobia), but a biological male pretending to be a female and not disclosing his true gender to potential dates or hookups is the definition of what a trap is in this context.

It's ridiculous how much of an issue some people have with LGBTQ people. A big part is the confusion of *genetic sex* (DNA blueprint), *biological sex* (Phenotype and Endocrine development), *gender* (masculine-feminie), *gender identity* (which gender, if any, a person feels they belong in), and *sexuality* (what sex and/or gender and/or identity one is physically and emotionally attracted to).

They're all different. DNA is just the blueprint, endocrine disruption, neuroendocrine feedback, and environment while growing up (leading to differeing phenotypal expression). Primary sex diffentiation (fetus starts to develop 'male' organs), secondary (older fetus differentiates brain structure and growth patterns), and then hormonal feedback (neuroendocrine disruption) in countless biological interactions through 20+ years of development.

Point is, it's very complicated, it _is_ confusing, and frankly, *experts* in psysiology, psychology, endocrinology, and more) are still hashing out the details. There's no way every layperson can be expected to know this, and some has to do with altering language and terminology, but it's also bullshit for non-experts to place value judgements or offer 'opinions' on something we just can't know. Also, a hefty dose of 'Get the fuck over it, don't be a fucknugget'.

I don't disagree that a trans woman with a 'feminine penis' is a woman.  I'm just curious about how we describe genital preferences now.    I think rightly so, we are conceptualizing gender independent from genitalia, but people are still attracted/unattracted to specific genitalia.  It seems to me that it's similar to general body preferences, except that I'd want to say that a person is superficial for being closed off to a relationship with someone of a certain height, facial structure, or ethnicity, but I do not (at present) think it unreasonable to be exclusive about genitalia. Is it reasonable for a person to rule out feminine-penis possessing partners?  Maybe because genitalia, unlike other attributes, are essential and constitutive components to certain kinds of sexual experiences?    I'm still confused because sexual experiences seem very tied up with the concept of sexual orientation, which I'm used to talking about along gender lines, but we've said that genitals don't determine gender.  So... genitals are part of a cluster-concept of gender just like any other physical gender-marker except perhaps that genitals have a bit more weight?

I would argue that it's more important to focus on whats true, rather than what kind of truth you can construct to create the outcome you want. You want there to be no violence against trans people, so you create a definition that gets around all the things about the transgender condition that has caused violence to be in sighted onto them in the past. Why is this approach better or more productive than simply educating people about the plight of transgenders, educating people about dysphoria and WHY and WHAT trans people feel? Don't you think its more important for people to understand what you're going through and understand why it's important for them to respect your choice to present as a woman, rather than creating loopholes so bigots can't say 'you tricked me' in defense  of actions all reasonable human beings already should know are completely indefensible? Like honestly, a feminine penis? You mean to suggest that because hormone therapy causes your dick to stop working, it's somehow a feminine penis now? The trans-person is not a woman, they are presenting as a woman, and we should treat them as woman, but when it comes down to questions like the one discussed in this video, you need to deal with technical details, and the technical detail and reality of it is, you aren't a woman. You deserve in all respects to be treated as one in any and all social situations (not including doctor visits of course) but you weren't born that way and you had to go through significant steps to present that way, and you know this. In your video about autogynephilia you seem to acknowledge that you are onto a woman, but that being feminine feels right and natural to you. I don't dispute that. That is what I think people should always say. Not that you are a woman, but that you feel right and natural displaying as one, and people should respect that not as a personal choice but as part of who you are. Why do you need to take it a step further, and say that trans woman are women, that a trans persons penis is just a feminine penis, that attraction to a trans woman is the equivalent of attraction to a cis one. It doesn't make transgenders less legitimate for people to say a man born a woman who lives there life as a woman is still in a technical sense biologically male. the problem shouldn't be, how to we change the meaning of transgender to remove stigmas so transgender people aren't attacked or hurt anymore, it should be how do we bring awareness to the fact that trans people are being treated unfairly and how do we educate people so they understand why we don't deserve to be treated unfairly, just as gay people don't deserve to be treated unfairly, because there is about the same amount of personal choice involved in the situation. You can either spend your entire life suppressing it or you can live with it.  I know I've rambled on for a long time but, look, there's reason I think its a good idea and that's because I was against trans people for a while. I lived in the bay area near san fransisco with a father who was homophobic and vigorously and unapologetically transphobic. I picked up some of his views when I was younger. Because I already had this bias for conservatism, when I saw all of these arguments for the left that I thought were totally unreasonable, I thought everything that my dad said about trans people was true, I was trans-phobic myself, because all the claims that were being thrown around sounded completely unreasonable to me, so I didn't lend any credence to the faact that transgenderism might be anything but prevision, or a grab for attention. It's only after dealing with forms of dysphoria myself while struggling with an eating disorder and hearing how similar (in certain ways not all ways) the feelings I felt regarding my body mirrored the ways that transpeople feel too. And I never would've come to that realization had I not broken the wall of absolute radical left ideas that get focused on in conservative circles and really looked at the source of transgenderism did I change my mind. Blaire is right. I don't like to point the accusatory finger, but when people like you make claims that aren't found in logical reason, you push others away from your cause. Straying from reality only widens the divide between the conservatives who are based in logic and reason (ie the skeptic community on youtube for instance), and that will only make it harder for you to deliver your message to those people.  Sorry for the long rant. I just don't have any friends to talk to in real life, and a lot of opinions.

I think it's so great you bring up the nuances of male and female penises and what that actually means. Let me open with that. We should talk about the mouthfeel more and everything! People genuinely do not know this. It's sad that bigotry and stigma do hold some back and hurt others. But while I like what you add to the conversation, you also remove other nuances from it.   That's why I feel I cannot be on anyone's side anymore. I can listen, yes, but I just have to disagree with everyone somewhere.  Example 1: Lesbians are a diverse group like any other, and even with zero transphobia, I am sure some cis and probably even a few trans lesbians will crave cis women for what cis women are and be attracted exclusively or predominantly to them or just to them and everyone that comes close enough. Because subtle differences exist here as well, to the other side so to speak - in some regards, in others none. But a lot of lesbians dont have any issue, and it comes to them naturally, and my guess is that it also depends on people's wider approach to gender and sexuality. Some of this is learned, some of this is hard-wired. Nature and nuture. Yet, very quickly cis lesbians with track records of being trans-friendly are thrown under the bus and labeled transphobes and TERFs (also transphobes) for what seems more an inability to express all these nuances I tried to lay out here correctly. Which is hard to do. For anyone. But fuck it, they're transphobes now and officially 'cancelled'. Let it be known in all the land. They then show a human response to the hostility?? Doubling down on all the transphobia, clearly (pls catch my sarcasm here).   Example 2: Your view of certain other trans women seems soul-crushingly unfair and even cruel from certain perspectives different than yours. I was seriously shocked at some bits. You dont mean to hurt, it's just the one-sidedness I guess. You really cannot speak for all trans women or trans people in general. No one can. Maybe you are referring to someone else, but people will think you mean women like Blaire White.  My impression is that you project patterns unto her like internalised bigotry with no possible way of proving it. It's a construct by you and your echo chamber. By doing that, you reduce and simplify her lived experience and intentions, and contribute to her demonisation, the on-going hate-train against her and her (trans and cis) supporters, while questioning her very agency and self-efficacy, and I think that's also harmful and diametrically opposed to your actual values. You do all the women that you do not and cannot represent as just one person or part of one ideological group a disservice.  Closing arguments: Not everything can be framed in 'politics' and 'power dynamics'. Like... as a fellow academic and a human being I so have to disagree with that approach in general, and vigorously so.  I wish I could support all trans people there are in the whole wide world, but that's actually impossible in your ideology. It makes me a persona non grata to stay away from.   Because of what *I think* are my nuanced compassionate views that I worked extremely hard on developing, by listening for endless hours to very different people, constantly questioning myself, I agree with everyone more or less and disagree with everyone more or less depending on what *complex multifactor issue* we are talking about today. To your side, unfortunately, this makes me an enemy who isn't trustworthy, who 'blindly believed bigoted lies', because you're blind - to the nuances I bring up that you have zero sensitivity for.  I have learned much from you, but your nuance only goes one way, especially here. Maybe these are just the limits of the human brain and this is why my head feels like it's gonna burst. Maybe it's because you are personally deeply affected yourself and this is what benefits you (in like a selfcare way, not an insidious way).  Maybe it's all connected to a general problem of the progressive left, where I actually had to free myself from many beliefs concerning my own life in order to become a stronger, more mentally healthy person. Let me correct myself: Not everything *should* be framed in 'politics' and 'power dynamics', especially not in such an absolute way, where it's the only approach, the only paradigm, the superior, single, valid ideology. The possible effects include projection, catastrophising and yes, self-victimisation.   Please listen better, try on different glasses, for real. Please try to work toward less hate and polarisation, for real.   Despite all my support for you and me seeing so much validity in your points of view over the years and still today, I recently lost a friend who means so much to me, who doesnt want to be my friend anymore, simply because I am able to also like Blaire as a person and see validity in her perspective - without attaching all that crap to her.  Seriously, I didnt realise the extent of misrepresentation and demonisation of Blaire that you also foster until I lost a close friend who has no idea who Blaire even is and what positive influence she also has. Why is Blaire not another trans women with legitimate concerns behind her statements, who adds to the picture, however much or little you want to allow her? And very importantly, who gives some trans people some much needed genuine confidence in themselves?   It's really the old Us vs. Them, isnt it? Intellectually underwhelming. Never right. I said nuance a lot here. I think it really is the key to understanding everything. But you let other people who also wrongfully project shit into her as well, just different shit, ruin her for you. We should all see each other more as one person, with one point of view, but then you really gotta stop the hate-train. (You realise what your movement does to her goes way beyond criticism right?)  I think politically no one has to be converted to any general perspective really. We can have all the plurality, including your streak of the rainbow, and all the freedom of speech within the laws against violence we currently have in many countries already. You just need people to practice healthy non-violent behaviours, in general, and work on their ability for putting themselves in other people's shoes, at least for a moment, so that they dont have to flip their shit over nothing that important. So that they can maybe soften their views a little, become less radical, less hostile. So that we can talk with each other.  But that's all I can spew for now. Sorry for the manifesto. Live long and prosper.

I like when you do videos like this much more than your 'explication' videos. In those videos where you just say what you think about the political issues you end up sounding quite preachy, not because you don't make legitimate and good points (you make quite good points), but instead because I don't feel that you give the opposing political perspective(s) their due (I know you make an effort, but I don't think you're that skilled with it).  The reason why I love these 'skit' videos quite a bit more is because--intentional or not--you actually portray a union of whats good about the major perspectives and whats bad about them.  I recall quite a while back that you suggested that you couldn't write 'high literature' or whatever term you used. I disagree. Though this isn't written, I think this is actually exactly what you were aiming for. I really believe that if you did set your mind to it, you could probably achieve that goal. Really, this is quite good stuff.  Though what you say about literature reinforcing social power dynamics and the like is true, its also true that there are a myriad of examples of literature doing the opposite and speaking truth to power. For example to consider Heart of Darkness a racist and sexist book is probably true; but its also a book that brought to light the horrors of the British Empire in Africa. I think you do something quite similar (albeit from the perspective of the politics in the left) with videos like these.  Don't take this as a recommendation not to make those explicative videos. I think those are important for you as well. I just wanted to emphasize how much these skit videos are fucking awesome.

There's obviously so many brilliantly clever things about this video, but I think Jackie Jackson is getting underappreciated here. A 'centrist' who cares about finding the truth and supposedly thinks debate is valuable IMMEDIATELY cuts off an actual bit of interesting discourse at 6:51 because it isn't relevant to her (or at-least, she fails to perceive how it is relevant to her). Also this moment is one where Jackie, the one with the media platform being used here, undermines Adria's desire to unpack and discuss the use of trap as a slur. As soon as it becomes clear that the TV show would lose credibility for even letting 'trap' be a part of the moot, the words are changed. This can be seen as a bit of ground given to Adria, but I also think that it's a valuable critique of how online political media is worse than ever for reframing things to isolate them from their context. Beholden to smaller and less diverse audiences, creators are financially incentivised to double down even further on giving people what they want than even old-school broadcast news media. This point is reiterated when there's a hard cut from a tearful Jackie to a cool and collected Jackie shooting the outro and promising to fix it in post, followed by her calling her producer to discuss very cynically how the two guests 'performed'.

The way to acceptance is not to scream at everyone for not being woke enough. It's not to make people have to walk on eggshells around you. How would you feel if you had to worry about getting screamed at, or at risk of losing family, friends, your job, or your livelihood because you said something that you didn't even know was incorrect or offensive?  That being said, I don't think the way to acceptance is letting bigotry just slide by, you have to actively fight against real maliciousness, but not people making dumb jokes to be edgy.  Also let me just say, people really do say stuff like 'You're a good tran/gay' or whatever and it's because a lot of people see the lgbt community as a joke. We're seen as a bunch of whiny babies who complain about everything under the sun. I think it's a generalisation to say that all right-wing trans youtubers are just pandering and struggling with internalized transphobia. There are really trans people out there with right-wing conservative views that are separate from their trans identity. And the 'I'm not a victim' mentality isn't necessarily a bad mentality. It promotes that in stead of crying about your shitty situation, you have to learn to deal with it and thrive regardless of your societal disadvantages. But that doesn't mean you shouldn't acknowledge those societal disadvantages and fight to diminish them.  You also shouldn't reach out to bigots and try to compromise with them, like 'alright, transgenderism is a mental illness, but I'm self-aware about it' or 'yeah, dating a trans chick as a man totally makes that man gay' or 'sure, non-binary / translesbian / bdsm trans people are freaky and crazy, but a hot, cis, straight trans woman is okay right?' As a result of those kind of comments, you see a lot of people on YouTube who might defend people like Blaire White to death because 'she is a conservative who speaks out against pc bullshit', but will still bully and harass every other trans person for being trans. So yeah, just wanted to add that. You make really good points in this video, but I also still think right-wing conservative trans people are valid.

Some of the talk show portion feels disingenuous.  Memes aside, I have no idea if 'the feminine penis' is so drastically different in sex than 'normal', but can we not admit that terms like 'lesbian' are ill-equipped to describe the spectrum of sexual identities and preferences that exist now?  Are you not contributing to the problem yourself by embracing this inherently limiting language?  Surely we can admit that not all women that are attracted to other women are going to be into a penis once the clothes come off, regardless of how 'feminine' it is, right?  I can only speak with confidence about my own sexuality, but genitalia does matter to me in bed.  It seems like you even sort of indirectly acknowledge this through the Adriana character.  Her defense against the host (regarding being attracted to men) is that she only likes 'feminine penis'.  Surely this is a much finer distinction than preference between penis and vagina, and the language you're choosing to use completely ignores these distinctions.  I'm not trans, so my stake in this whole thing is quite low, but the treatment of trans people is very much spotlit, so it's hard to ignore.  From the outside, it really just seems like it's often the wrong things that are being focused on.  'Wrong' in this context meaning things which are either not productive or are actively counter-productive to perceived causes.  I understand you've changed your views a lot over time anyways and that you don't claim to have all the answers, but it's undeniable that you have a large online presence on this front, so I feel like pressing you to be self-critical, especially given that these videos are made to be more easily consumed while also being distinctly un-academic, is important.  Hope you're well, and I hope you'll address some of this at some point.

Here's one harsh truth I've had to face in my own activism: Being right has no value if you're not persuasive. And what I mean is, there are many ways of saying the same thing, and oftentimes the goal is more important than what's actually being said or done. So I wish that we, as a community of well-meaning people, would give some thought to how we communicate things. It's hard being nice to people who say hurtful things, but if there's a chance that it creates a relationship where change is possible, then perhaps it's worth at least considering? Well this sure was a video to watch while I was already sad, dysphoric, and drunk.  But still, it was a fabulous piece of work. Tiffany was obviously the show-stealer, but I liked how Adria managed to ultimately stand as an independent woman against the roles pushed on her by both external heterocisnormativity and internal biases w/i trans/queer communities. But there was also some (minor, praxis-oriented) criticisms of her as well; maybe we as a culture should be talking about girl-dick, but a debate with Tiffany overseen by Jackie was neither the time nor the place. But she was also willing to defend Tiffany the _moment_ that Jackie started attacking her.  And I loved the quieter moment where they talked to each other 'off-camera'. I really wish we had gotten more of that exchange; it turned the tide to focus sympathy on Tiffany, yes, but these are two characters with a *lot* to say to one another. I hope we get to see them interact again.  A lovely piece of work, Natalie. Probably your best yet.

I've dated cis women who had a lot of body hair.  Their body hair did not make them 'male'.  I've dated cis women who had almost no chest fat.  Their lack of breasts did not make them 'male'.  I've dated cis women who had large, strong noses.  Their noses did not make them 'male'.  I've dated cis women who had broad shoulders and narrow hips.  Their torso physiology did not make them 'male'.  Certainly, all these markers inform a general sense of what society considers 'feminine', but I don't see how they do anything to determine who is 'female' or not.  Certainly, self-identifying as a cis-het male, my romantic interest is directed toward my own personal concept of the feminine -- but I think it's absurd for anyone to take *their* concept of what is 'feminine', & try to extrapolate that onto whether or not *someone else* is 'female' -- the question should never be 'is this person [male/female] enough for me to date?', the question should be 'does this person conform enough to *my* view of [masculine/feminine] for me to date?'  Yes, I'm one of those evil post-modernist Marxists who thinks that binary-gender structure is no longer relevant to modern people's lives -- I'm here, I'm post-gender, get used to it...

I'm not sure if I'd be so hard on the word 'Trap'. Sure, if one were to interpret it literally, it's pretty bad, but you have to consider the context. It became a popular term not just because of anime fans, but hentai fans particularly who would look at a pretty cartoon lady and then BOOM PENIS. Like 'are traps gay?' no one is asking the question literally or seriously and no one thinks deeply about the word 'trap' when saying it or typing it. It (along with 'shemale') also slowly became a term that became its own definition of something in that context, almost like a fictional race of third-gendered beings that we wish existed but don't. Violence against transfolk has been a thing decades before the tongue-in-cheek word floated around hentai porn communities and I don't believe the word itself is a malicious slur, even if I avoid using it myself. Trying to break down and philosophically dissect relatively harmless colloquialisms and taking them way more seriously than the users ever did is exactly the kind of killjoy Ivory Tower ramblings that you criticize in 'The Left'.

I originally posted this as a reply, but I think it's an important point that people should consider: regarding 'transphobia is racist,' European colonialism OFTEN involved painting the genders/gender systems of colonized peoples as deviant, dangerous, and inferior, so forcing colonized peoples to conform to Western gender roles, just like the spread of Christianity, had a significant role in manufacturing 1. a justification for colonization and 2. suppressing dissent--in both colonizing and colonized peoples! Restricting and simplifying European gender norms in a way that posited *our* genders as superior made it easier to create an 'us vs them' divide, and stripping colonized peoples of their gender/ed traditions was pretty obviously demoralizing, dehumanizing, and was another way to turn the people who could conform to the colonial regime against those who couldn't. Not to say that there weren't damaging, restrictive gender systems that existed before European colonialism ofc, but the hegemonic (mainstream/powerful) gender system of '2 sexes, 2 genders that always link up with each other' is a relatively recent and very Western invention.  I don't know if it was Natalie's intent to invoke that history, but regardless it's an incredibly clever line, because just like 'the feminine penis' what Adria is saying sounds ridiculous and absurd without context, but with a little education you realize she's totally right. It also suits her character, imo, as someone who's a little self-serious but ahead of the curve politically. Excellent writing all around, love it!

When I see Tiffany portrayed, I see her as deeply dysphoric and truly terrified of society's reaction, which explains her adoption of a reactionary political stance while desperately trying to fit into the realm of social acceptability, while fearing that she'll never be accepted by even those with whom she agrees politically. The predominate emotion dominating her entire being is terror. Understandable, given the society we live in and the dangers it presents to transpeople.  Adriana, on the other hand, is equally aware of society's reaction to transgender people, but reacts in an entirely different way, with complete and utter defiance. As Tiffany responds with fear (I would say mortal terror masked beneath a superficial veneer of ultra-femininity, but I digress...), Adriana responds with a militant 'I am who I am, and if you don't like, you can fuck off!' mentality. In essence, Adriana has no more fucks to give. She would rather change society by being loud and proud, while refusing to allow society to dictate who and what she is. She would rather take the control over her life, which Tiffany secretly admires and respects, but loathes herself for lacking.   Ultimately, I deeply understand the frustration Adriana exhibits regarding Tiffany's attacking her, when they should stand in solidarity with one another to form a united front which says 'Fuck all!' to the world. She would rather look beyond the ascetics of one's appearance as a means of approaching transphobia and attack the issue head-on, but is frustrated by attacks from who she perceives as an obvious ally. There is a warrior mentality about Adriana that I deeply respect. She's a fighter and she's damn proud of it (as well she should be, in my mind!).  Am I wrong in perceiving a sexual tension between Tiffany and Adriana? Throughout the video, I wondered if the two set aside their different reactions to transphobia and support one another, that they would both likely end up the stronger for it. Tiffany can temper the fires within Adriana, her knack for confrontation and convince her to instead adopt a more diplomatic approach. While Adriana can recognize the deep insecurities that plague Tiffany and unravel them by reinforcing the reality that Tiffany is beautiful, that she is worthy of love and can truly be her gorgeous self no matter what anyone says; that ultra-fem or not, Tiffany has a valid place in this world. As a Trans Woman, 10 years after transition, I would have to say this is a great video. Lots for people to contemplate. Mostly, I saw myself at various points in my life. The activism, the alcoholism, and the self loathing. I think you've been honest about what is going on in our heads, Natalie, as we try to navigate through society as the people we see ourselves as, mainly Women. But, also feeling outside of the binary of Man and Woman at times. Although, most of us are loathe to say so, myself included, I feel we are different than natal Men or Women. I know, I know, it doesn't help the cause. But we can talk to each other about it, can't we?  Internally, from my point of view, I wasn't raised as a boy, I was raised as a Trans kid. Very scared and messed up. Spending nearly a year of my young life institutionalized because of depression. Not willing to tell a soul about myself, until I opened up to my then wife(1999ish), then I couldn't get the genie back in the bottle, so I hit the bottle. Until, of course, I crashed and had to deal with it. Or die. So I transitioned got divorced, but stayed friends, only to watch her die of cancer (2008). Meanwhile, I met my current partner, who I am still with. The good, the bad, the old, and the new, all happening at the same time. It's kinda boring now, but I'm getting used to it. Life isn't perfect, but it isn't as chaotic either.  All of this leading to me today. 55 years old with a girlfriend, also trans (yea!), of 14 years. I look back and it all could have ended up very badly, on many an occasion. But, it didn't and I'm still here, so I can watch something like this video. I'm glad I made it, and not to sound corny, but YOU CAN TOO. If I could give you any advice, don't be Tiffany. Not everyone is going to like you. Fuck'em! Find the people that do like you, for being you, and stay with them.   Great job as always Natalie. It's great to see you grow and change. So far, you're doing great. Keep the videos coming. Can't wait to talk about this with my partner later. Cheers from the Badgerland.

Contra I think again nails the subject out of the park.  There is so much going on in this video and many of the points are issues many find to have with the trans movement.  Perhaps the issue is that once again a movement is way too focused on one issue, opposed to doing a broad focus.  Stop making it JUST about trans, but just push for an end to gender specific rules and limits.  Notice how in this vid 'femininity' is being connected to appearance, and styles, and behavior.  THIS is the problem in my eyes.  When a woman is called butch for wearing pants or more 'manly styles' there is a problem.  When a man is called 'sissy' because he chooses to wear so called feminine clothing, there is a problem...and when loving someone of the same sex as yourself is somehow STILL a bad thing...there is a problem.  *** It seems many commenters are thinking this video is an either or sort of vid, or Natalie is making one side look one way, and the other side look another.  I really do think what Natalie was doing...and did well, is that the arguments of the two sides DO conicide, but also that there are some arguments that to those we are trying to see our side of, see as absurd 'female penis, male vagina', for a vast majority these terms put up a wall in conversation.  In my eyes what needs to happen is for a broadening of what it is to be masculine, and what it means to be feminine, and for those that like to express as a mix to be free to do so without threat of losing their job, home, family, friends.  In many ways the trans movement as it is is reinforcing gender rules and limits.  By looking at someone such as myself (a practitioner of androgyny) as 'trans in denial' they are making it like if a man varies from the 'normal' definition of male, he MUST be trans.  If you don't think this is the case, then if you are male, go to your next jury service in a skirt suit..see what happens.  (it will be a good day when this sort of thing is not a factor).  There are too many connections of one's sex or gender with outward appearance and behaviors, and to me the trans movement in too many ways supports these.
